---

! 1. What a profile looks like

Here is a complete profile for a flat list of books.

Source JSON:

```
{
  "books": [
    { "title": "Dune",        "author": "Frank Herbert",  "year": 1965 },
    { "title": "Neuromancer", "author": "William Gibson", "year": 1984 },
    { "title": "Kindred",     "author": "Octavia Butler", "year": 1979 }
  ]
}
```

The profile:

```
{
  "records": "{{books[*]}}",
  "tw-fields": {
    "title": "{{author}}: {{title}}",
    "tags":  "Book"
  },
  "custom-fields": {
    "year": "{{year}}"
  }
}
```

After Convert + Apply you get three tiddlers:

|!Title                          |!`tags` |!`year` |
|Frank Herbert: Dune             |Book    |1965    |
|William Gibson: Neuromancer     |Book    |1984    |
|Octavia Butler: Kindred         |Book    |1979    |

Each block is doing one thing:

* `records` says //iterate `books[*]`, one tiddler per element//.
* `tw-fields` populates the tiddler's built-in fields.  `{{author}}`
  and `{{title}}` are //tokens// — they look up the named path in the
  current record.
* `custom-fields` does the same for any other field you want on the
  resulting tiddler.

That's the whole vocabulary.  The next sections take each piece apart.

---

! 2. Anatomy

A profile is a JSON object with up to three top-level keys, in any
order:

|!Key             |!What it does                                                  |
|`records`        |A template identifying the source array to iterate             |
|`tw-fields`      |Bindings for built-in tiddler fields (`title`, `tags`, …)      |
|`custom-fields`  |Bindings for every other field on the resulting tiddler        |

`records` is mandatory.  `tw-fields` and `custom-fields` are both
optional, but at least one of them must contain a `title` binding so
each resulting tiddler has a title.  In practice you'll always have
`title` under `tw-fields`.

!! 2.1 `records`

`records` is a //template// containing exactly one path token wrapped
in `{{ … }}`:

```
"records": "{{books[*]}}"
```

The path inside must resolve to an array.  The `[*]` operator says
//for every element of that array, emit one record//.  See §4.3 for
the full path grammar.

A profile produces one tiddler per record element — three books
above, twelve activities for a three-day Iceland trip, however many
your source has.

`records` can walk through multiple `[*]`s in one path:
`{{days[*].activities[*]}}` produces one record per activity across
all days.  See §4.4.

!! 2.2 `tw-fields`

The built-in TiddlyWiki fields go here.  Conventionally that means
`title`, `tags`, `text`, `type`, `created`, `modified`, `creator`,
`modifier`.  Each maps to a binding (§3) producing the value written
to that field on each resulting tiddler.

Typical bindings:

* `"title": "{{author}}: {{title}}"` — a title built from two source
  fields.
* `"tags": "Book {{genre|split-commas}}"` — a static word plus a
  list-formatted source value.
* `"created": "{{created_at|iso-to-date}}"` — an ISO timestamp
  converted to TiddlyWiki's `YYYYMMDDhhmmssXXX` format.

You don't have to bind every built-in field.  Anything you skip is
left unset on the resulting tiddler (TW will fill in `created` and
`modified` automatically if you don't).

!! 2.3 `custom-fields`

Everything else — domain-specific fields you want on the resulting
tiddler — goes here.  Same binding syntax, same path expressions,
same transforms.  The only practical difference from `tw-fields` is
that the field name isn't constrained by TiddlyWiki convention; pick
whatever fits your data.

```
"custom-fields": {
  "year":      "{{year}}",
  "publisher": "{{publisher.name}}",
  "isbn-13":   "{{isbn}}"
}
```

The validator catches collisions between `tw-fields` and
`custom-fields` (error code `field-redefined`) so the same field
name can't appear in both blocks.

---

! 3. Bindings

A //binding// is a string template.  Most bindings are short — one
token, sometimes a token plus literal text.  Examples already
appeared above; this section names the parts.

!! 3.1 Plain text

A binding with no `{{ … }}` is used verbatim:

```
"tags": "Book"
```

Every resulting tiddler gets the literal string `Book` as its `tags`.

!! 3.2 `{{path}}` tokens

`{{path}}` substitutes the value at `path` (resolved against the
current record) into the binding.  Numbers, booleans, and null
auto-stringify; arrays and objects become their JSON serialisations.

```
"title":   "{{title}}"
"caption": "{{author}}"
```

!! 3.3 Mixing tokens and text

A binding can interleave any number of tokens with surrounding text:

```
"title": "{{author}}: {{title}} ({{year}})"
```

For the first book above this produces `Frank Herbert: Dune (1965)`.

Single `{` or `}` characters in a binding are literal — you only
need the double form when you want a token.

!! 3.4 Missing paths

If a token's path doesn't resolve (the field is missing on this
particular record), the token expands to an empty string.  No error.
This makes profiles tolerant of irregular input: some records may
have a field that others don't, and you don't have to special-case
each one.

If you //want// to be strict, eyeball the staging area before Apply
— it shows the resolved values for every tiddler about to be written.

---

! 4. Path expressions

A //path expression// is what goes inside `{{ … }}`.  It walks the
source JSON.  Most paths are short; the syntax scales to handle
arbitrary nesting when you need it.

!! 4.1 Keys and dots

Dot-separate object keys:

```
{{publisher.name}}
{{address.country.code}}
```

Keys can contain anything that isn't `.`, `[`, `]`, or `/`.

!! 4.2 Array indices

Numeric brackets pick a specific element:

```
{{authors[0]}}
{{tags[2]}}
```

Useful when the source structure is fixed (position 0 is always the
primary author, etc.).

!! 4.3 `[*]` — iteration

The star says //iterate every element//.  In `records` (§2.1), `[*]`
defines what becomes a tiddler.  In a //binding// token, `[*]` is
not allowed (validator error `binding-token-star`) — bindings must
resolve to a single value per record, and `[*]` produces many.

If you want to flatten an array into a binding (e.g. a list of
tags), the `split-commas` and `split-to-titles` transforms (§5)
format an array as a wikitext list.

!! 4.4 Nested iteration

`records` can use multiple `[*]`s to flatten nested arrays.  Given:

```
{
  "days": [
    { "date": "2023-09-01", "activities": [...] },
    { "date": "2023-09-02", "activities": [...] }
  ]
}
```

a profile with `"records": "{{days[*].activities[*]}}"` produces one
tiddler per activity across all days.  Three days × four activities
each = twelve tiddlers.

!! 4.5 Ancestor scopes — `..`

Once a profile iterates `days[*].activities[*]`, the "current record"
is an activity object.  Activity-level fields are reachable as
`{{name}}`, `{{duration}}`, etc.  But what about the day's `date` or
the trip's `country`?  Those live one or two levels //above// the
current record.

The `..` segment walks up one iteration scope:

|!Token                       |!Reaches                      |
|`{{name}}`                   |the current activity's name   |
|`{{../date}}`                |the day's date (one up)       |
|`{{../../trip-name}}`        |the trip name (two up, root)  |

Stack as many `..` as you have `[*]`s in `records`.  More than that
is an error (`binding-parent-too-deep`).

!! 4.6 Bare-array roots

Sometimes the source isn't an object but a top-level array:

```
[
  { "id": 1, "name": "Alice" },
  { "id": 2, "name": "Bob" }
]
```

The records path can start with `[*]`:

```
"records": "{{[*]}}"
```

Combined with nested iteration: `"records": "{{[*].pages[*]}}"`.

---

! 5. Transforms

A //transform// is a named function that reshapes a token's value
before substitution.  Pipe a transform onto a token with `|`:

|!Token                              |!Effect                                     |
|`{{title\|to-upper-case}}`          |`"Dune"` → `"DUNE"`                         |
|`{{genre\|split-commas}}`           |`"sci-fi, classic"` → `"sci-fi classic"`    |
|`{{created_at\|iso-to-date}}`       |`"2026-05-17T21:36:24Z"` → `"20260517213624000"` |

!! 5.1 Chaining

Multiple transforms run left-to-right:

```
{{title|to-lower-case|slugify}}
```

The output of `to-lower-case` becomes the input to `slugify`.  No
arbitrary limit on chain length.

!! 5.2 Plugin-shipped transforms

|!Name                |!Input → Output                                                                |
|`html-to-wikitext`   |Placeholder for upcoming HTML conversion; currently pass-through               |
|`split-commas`       |`"a, b, c"` (or array) → `"a b c"`, `[[ ]]`-quoting any item with whitespace   |
|`split-to-titles`    |Like `split-commas`, but //every// item is `[[ ]]`-wrapped                     |
|`timestamp-to-date`  |Numeric epoch (seconds or ms) → TW `YYYYMMDDhhmmssXXX` UTC                     |
|`iso-to-date`        |ISO 8601 string → TW `YYYYMMDDhhmmssXXX` UTC                                   |
|`to-upper-case`      |`"hello"` → `"HELLO"`                                                          |
|`to-lower-case`      |`"HELLO"` → `"hello"`                                                          |
|`to-title-case`      |`"hello world"` → `"Hello World"`                                              |
|`slugify`            |`"Hello, World!"` → `"hello-world"`                                            |

!! 5.3 User-defined transforms

Add your own by creating a tiddler tagged
`$:/tags/json-convert/transform`.  JavaScript bodies expose `value`
(the input string) and return the transformed string; wikitext
bodies run as filter expressions with `value` in scope.  See the
[[Usage guide|$:/plugins/crosseye/json-convert/usage]] §8 for full
details and worked examples.

The transform's name is its tiddler title (or `caption`, if set).
Names appear in the editor's Browse-modal transform picker alongside
the built-ins.

---

! 6. Writing a profile by hand

You don't have to use the editor.  A profile is just a JSON tiddler
tagged `$:/tags/json-convert/profile`.

!! 6.1 The minimum

```
title: My First Profile
tags: $:/tags/json-convert/profile
type: application/json

{
  "records": "{{[*]}}",
  "tw-fields": {
    "title": "{{name}}"
  }
}
```

Drag the source JSON into the Console, pick ''My First Profile'' from
the profile dropdown, Convert, Apply.

!! 6.2 Naming

Use any human-readable title — `Example Trip Itinerary`,
`Moodle Quiz`, `Bookshelf Import`.  No `$:/` namespace required.
The plugin watches the tag, not the title.

!! 6.3 Common gotchas

* ''Token vs. literal''. `{{author}}` is a token; `{author}` is the
  literal text `{author}` — no substitution.  Double braces are
  required.
* ''Quoting JSON''. `records` is a JSON string, so the binding inside
  is `"{{books[*]}}"` (the outer quotes belong to JSON; the inner
  braces belong to the binding language).
* ''Field collisions''. If a key appears in both `tw-fields` and
  `custom-fields`, the validator reports `field-redefined`.  Pick
  one block.
* ''Trailing commas''. JSON doesn't allow them.  The validator will
  surface a `bad-shape` error.
* ''Forgetting to tag''. An untagged profile won't appear in the
  Console's dropdown.  The tag is `$:/tags/json-convert/profile`.

!! 6.4 Validating

The fastest validation loop is to open your hand-written profile in
the editor (Console → select profile → ''Edit'').  The editor runs
the validator live and shows every error in-line with click-to-scroll
links.  Errors that aren't editor-resolvable (e.g. a typo in the
JSON itself) show the raw error code from the
[[Usage guide|$:/plugins/crosseye/json-convert/usage]] §10.4.

---

! 7. Building a profile with the editor

The editor is the recommended way to build and tweak profiles.  It
handles the JSON serialisation, runs live validation, and offers
point-and-click pickers backed by the actual source JSON.

''Screenshot needed:'' the Editor open on a sample profile, with the
records path field at top, the source JSON pane on the right, and
the `tw-fields` / `custom-fields` tables in the middle.

!! 7.1 Opening the editor

From the Console:

* ''New…'' opens an empty editor.  Pick the source JSON, name the
  profile, start binding.
* ''Edit'' opens the currently-selected profile.  Edits save live as
  you type (debounced ~200ms); see §7.8.

!! 7.2 The Sample JSON pane

The right-hand pane shows the source JSON the editor is using as its
//example// — what every path is resolved against in the live
preview.  The Console and the editor //share// this state, so
whatever's in the Console source area is also what the editor uses
for path resolution.

If you don't have a source ready, paste any small example.  All the
pickers (records, paths, fields) walk this JSON to suggest names.

!! 7.3 Picking the records path

Above the fields tables is a single ''records'' field with a
''Browse'' button.  Click Browse and a modal opens showing the source
JSON as a tree.

''Screenshot needed:'' the ''Pick the records path'' modal — the
JSON-shape tree with one of the arrays highlighted, ready for
selection.

Click ''copy'' on the array you want to iterate.  If you click on a
specific element (e.g. `[0]`), the picker rewrites that to `[*]`
automatically so the records path matches all siblings, not just the
one you happened to click on.

!! 7.4 Adding `tw-fields` bindings

Below the records field are two tables: ''tw-fields'' and
''custom-fields''.  Each row is a single binding.  To add a row,
type the field name (`title`, `tags`, etc.) and click ''Add''; then
click the new row's ''Browse'' button to fill the binding template.

''Screenshot needed:'' the `tw-fields` table mid-edit, with a few
rows filled in, cursor in the title row, and the Browse modal open
showing ''Current record'' tree plus an ''Ancestor: `../`'' tree.

The path modal shows one tree per scope:

* ''Current record'' — the shape of the iteration target.  Pick
  fields here for tokens like `{{name}}`.
* ''Ancestor: `../`'' (and `../../`, etc. for deeper records paths)
  — fields one or more scopes up.  Picking from these scopes inserts
  the appropriate `../` prefix automatically.

Each click on a tree row's ''copy'' button inserts a `{{path}}`
token at the cursor position in the binding input.  Type literal
text between tokens for compound bindings like
`"{{author}}: {{title}}"`.

!! 7.5 Adding `custom-fields` bindings

Same workflow, different table.  Custom field names are
user-defined; the editor accepts anything that doesn't collide with
a `tw-fields` row.

!! 7.6 The Browse modal in binding mode

The modal's ''Optional transform'' dropdown attaches a transform to
every path you pick from this modal session.  Useful when you're
binding several date fields in a row and want `|iso-to-date` on all
of them: pick the transform once, then click your way through the
source.

You can always edit the binding manually after picking — chain more
transforms, add literal text, whatever.

!! 7.7 The pass-through field picker

When the source has dozens of fields and you want most of them as
custom-fields with their JSON keys as field names, the ''Custom
Fields'' header has a ''Pick fields…'' button.  It opens a checkbox
tree of every leaf in the source.

''Screenshot needed:'' the ''Pick fields'' modal open on the Moodle
Gradebook sample, showing the checkbox tree with editable field-name
inputs to the right of the checkboxes.

Tick the leaves you want; they land as custom-fields bindings on
Apply, with their JSON key auto-flattened (slugified) into a tiddler
field name you can override inline.  The picker supports tri-state
''All'' (header), Select-all / Clear-all bulk buttons, and
inline-editable field names.

!! 7.8 Live save, debounce, revert

The editor saves your draft live, debounced ~200ms after the last
keystroke.  No ''Save'' button.  When you open a profile via
''Edit'', the original is snapshotted; the editor's revert action
restores the snapshot if you decide your edits weren't what you
wanted.

